  <article id="about-article-33EF85AR" class="about_pub-article">
    <h1>About</h1>
    Brend et al. conducted a study to understand how residential childcare workers (RCW) in Canada experience work-related pride and achievement. They found that RCWs often feel proud and accomplished when they have strong, trusting relationships with the children and youth they care for. These positive feelings are important because they can help prevent staff turnover, which is a common issue in this field. The study suggests that the wellbeing of RCWs is closely linked to the quality of their relationships with the children, highlighting the importance of mutual trust and connection. This insight could help improve strategies for supporting RCWs and enhancing their job satisfaction, ultimately benefiting both the workers and the children in their care.
  </article>

  <article id="abstract-article-33EF85AR" class="abstract-article">
    <h1>Scientific abstract</h1>
    Multiple risk and protective factors influence the wellbeing and retention of child protective and youth justice professionals. Less attention has been given to empirically understand how residential childcare workers (RCW) experience these factors. A sense of pride and of achievement may be related to competence and satisfaction, which have been identified as protective factors against staff turnover.MethodsResponses to the Secure Base Interview Protocol question “What aspects of caring for (name of child in their care) have given you the greatest sense of pride or achievement?” were extracted from individual interview transcripts from Canadian RCW and analyzed using the Interpretive Description methodology. Themes were aggregated using the thematic analysis technique to create descriptions of RCW pride and achievement.ResultsThe RCW identified many experiences of work-related pride and achievement while caring for children and youth. These positive experiences were described to occur contingent on the level of mutuality and trust in the helping relationship shared between the RCW and child or youth in their care.DiscussionThe reciprocal nature of the relationships described by RCW that gave rise to their felt sense of pride and accomplishment is a novel finding. Future work is indicated to better understand how protective factors related to RCW wellbeing may indeed be relationally constructed and dependent.
  </article>
